TASK 1 - Depth First Search (DFS) from node A


DFS uses recursion (or explicit Stack).
marked[v] = true when vertex v is visited.
edgeTo[w] = v means we reached w from v for the first time.

Detailed trace (book style):

dfs(A)
  check C -> not marked
  dfs(C)
    check A -> marked, skip
    check B -> not marked
    dfs(B)
      check A -> marked, skip
      check C -> marked, skip
      check E -> not marked
      dfs(E)
        check G -> not marked
        dfs(G)
          check F -> not marked
          dfs(F)
            check G -> marked, skip
            check E -> marked, skip
            F done
          check B -> marked, skip
          G done
        check F -> marked, skip
        check B -> marked, skip
        E done
      check G -> marked, skip
      B done
    check D -> not marked
    dfs(D)
      check C -> marked, skip
      check A -> marked, skip
      D done
    C done
  check B -> marked, skip
  check D -> marked, skip
  A done

edgeTo[] after DFS:
  edgeTo[C] = A    (reached C from A)
  edgeTo[B] = C    (reached B from C)
  edgeTo[E] = B    (reached E from B)
  edgeTo[G] = E    (reached G from E)
  edgeTo[F] = G    (reached F from G)
  edgeTo[D] = C    (reached D from C)

DFS Visit Order: A -> C -> B -> E -> G -> F -> D

TASK 2 - Breadth First Search (BFS) from node A

BFS uses a Queue (FIFO - First In First Out).
distTo[w] = distance from source to w in number of edges.
edgeTo[w] = v means we reached w from v for the first time.

Detailed trace (book style):

Start: enqueue A, mark A
Queue: [A]
distTo: A=0, all others=infinity

Dequeue A (distTo=0)
  check C -> not marked, enqueue C, edgeTo[C]=A, distTo[C]=1
  check B -> not marked, enqueue B, edgeTo[B]=A, distTo[B]=1
  check D -> not marked, enqueue D, edgeTo[D]=A, distTo[D]=1
Queue: [C, B, D]

Dequeue C (distTo=1)
  check A -> marked, skip
  check B -> marked (in queue), skip
  check D -> marked (in queue), skip
Queue: [B, D]

Dequeue B (distTo=1)
  check A -> marked, skip
  check C -> marked, skip
  check E -> not marked, enqueue E, edgeTo[E]=B, distTo[E]=2
  check G -> not marked, enqueue G, edgeTo[G]=B, distTo[G]=2
Queue: [D, E, G]

Dequeue D (distTo=1)
  check C -> marked, skip
  check A -> marked, skip
Queue: [E, G]

Dequeue E (distTo=2)
  check G -> marked (in queue), skip
  check F -> not marked, enqueue F, edgeTo[F]=E, distTo[F]=3
  check B -> marked, skip
Queue: [G, F]

Dequeue G (distTo=2)
  check F -> marked (in queue), skip
  check B -> marked, skip
Queue: [F]

Dequeue F (distTo=3)
  check G -> marked, skip
  check E -> marked, skip
Queue: [] done

edgeTo[] after BFS:
  edgeTo[C] = A    (reached C from A, distance 1)
  edgeTo[B] = A    (reached B from A, distance 1)
  edgeTo[D] = A    (reached D from A, distance 1)
  edgeTo[E] = B    (reached E from B, distance 2)
  edgeTo[G] = B    (reached G from B, distance 2)
  edgeTo[F] = E    (reached F from E, distance 3)

distTo[] shortest distances from A:
  A=0, C=1, B=1, D=1, E=2, G=2, F=3

BFS Visit Order: A -> C -> B -> D -> E -> G -> F

TASK 4 - Shortest Path: Edinburgh to Dundee
(Dijkstra's Algorithm)

Scottish road network:

Edinburgh – Glasgow: 70
Edinburgh – Stirling: 50
Edinburgh – Perth: 100
Glasgow – Stirling: 50
Stirling – Perth: 40
Perth – Dundee: 60

Dijkstra's Algorithm step by step:

Initial state:
  distTo[Edinburgh] = 0
  distTo[Stirling]  = infinity
  distTo[Perth]     = infinity
  distTo[Dundee]    = infinity
  distTo[Inverness] = infinity
  PriorityQueue: [(Edinburgh, 0)]

Step 1: Visit Edinburgh (closest, distance=0)
  relax Edinburgh -> Stirling:  0+36=36  < inf  -> update, edgeTo[Stirling]=Edinburgh
  relax Edinburgh -> Perth:     0+44=44  < inf  -> update, edgeTo[Perth]=Edinburgh
  distTo: Edinburgh=0, Stirling=36, Perth=44, Dundee=inf, Inverness=inf
  PriorityQueue: [(Stirling,36), (Perth,44)]

Step 2: Visit Stirling (closest unvisited, distance=36)
  relax Stirling -> Perth:   36+31=67  > 44   -> no update
  relax Stirling -> Dundee:  36+50=86  < inf  -> update, edgeTo[Dundee]=Stirling
  distTo: Edinburgh=0, Stirling=36, Perth=44, Dundee=86, Inverness=inf
  PriorityQueue: [(Perth,44), (Dundee,86)]

Step 3: Visit Perth (closest unvisited, distance=44)
  relax Perth -> Dundee:    44+21=65  < 86   -> update, edgeTo[Dundee]=Perth
  relax Perth -> Inverness: 44+112=156 < inf -> update, edgeTo[Inverness]=Perth
  distTo: Edinburgh=0, Stirling=36, Perth=44, Dundee=65, Inverness=156
  PriorityQueue: [(Dundee,65), (Inverness,156)]

Step 4: Visit Dundee (closest unvisited, distance=65)
  Destination reached!

Shortest path: Edinburgh → Stirling → Perth → Dundee
Total distance: 150 miles
